    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/ddQNg.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 7395051,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 5627271,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5627271/r%c3%a9mi-bantos",
                "reputation": 1977,
                "display_name": "R&#233;mi Bantos"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1661264102,
            "creation_date": 1660399677,
            "body": "<p>To achieve strong encapsulation with Java, you could make use of maven modules per layer, left, right and domain.\nI have not tried but I guess Java 9 modules would also help here. Check <a href=\"https://medium.com/swlh/a-practical-example-of-applying-java-modules-in-a-hexagonal-architecture-d345deec654b\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">this link<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p>Another approach I use for the sake of simplicity and code readability, is to use a single module, without strong encapsulation, but different packages per layers, one for domain, another for infra..<\/p>\n<p>And, to <strong>enforce architecture rules<\/strong> within this module, like hexagonal ones, I usually define a unit test which fails in case of any violation, for example when some domain package code directly depends on a technical API client implem defined outside the domain.\nSo far I have used <a href=\"https://www.archunit.org/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Archunit<\/a> framework for that.<\/p>\n<p>Also I prefer this approach because, as a developer or new joiner for example, IMO it is much easier to break some architecture rules / encapsulation patterns, not being aware till the code review, rather than breaking / ignoring a test which would fail the build, and which would also act as a spec for these rules.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 73344956,
            "question_id": 73198158,
            "last_edit_date": 1661264102
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/416696430ab23f397a5dbeda73e72896?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 5289146,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 4222206,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4222206/queeg",
                "reputation": 9940,
                "display_name": "queeg"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1659433044,
            "creation_date": 1659379531,
            "body": "<p>What you want to achieve is definitey doable in Java.<\/p>\n<p>There are numerous examples - for example check out the JAXP library:<\/p>\n<p>While you use the DocumentBuilderFactory to instantiate a DocumentBuilder and ultimately parse a Document, everything but the factory are interfaces abstracting away a concise implementation, which is the pattern you are aiming at.<\/p>\n<p>To get more concise: All that you need to do is come up with the right combination of classes, interfaces and packages. Have a look at <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_design_pattern\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Design Patterns<\/a> which describe what you need to do. The book <a href=\"https://springframework.guru/gang-of-four-design-patterns/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">&quot;Design Patterns&quot; by the Gang of Four<\/a> is very helpful in that respect.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 73198239,
            "question_id": 73198158,
            "last_edit_date": 1659433044
        }
